{"title_page": "Clue cell", "text_new": "[[File:Clue cells - CDC PHIL 3720.jpg|thumb|right|Bacteria obscuring the borders of vaginal epithelial cells, giving them a stippled appearance]]\n[[File:Vaginal wet mount with a clue cell.jpg|thumb|right|[[Vaginal wet mount]] with [[sodium chloride|NaCl]] preparation, showing a clue cell at bottom left, and two normal epithelial cells.]]\n'''Clue cells''' are [[epithelial]] cells of the [[vagina]] that get their distinctive stippled appearance by being covered with [[bacteria]]. The etymology behind the term \"clue\" cell derives from the original research article from Gardner and Dukes describing the characteristic cells. The name was chosen for its brevity in describing the [[sine qua non]] of [[bacterial vaginosis]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gardner|first=Herman|author2=Dukes, Charles|title=Haemophilus vaginalis vaginitis: A newly defined specific infection previously classified \"nonspecific\" vaginitis|journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology|date=May 1955|pages=962\u2013976|pmid=14361525|volume=69|issue=5|doi=10.1016/0002-9378(55)90095-8}}<!--|accessdate=24 January 2013--></ref>\n\nThey are a [[medical sign]] of bacterial vaginosis, particularly that caused by ''[[Gardnerella vaginalis]]'',<ref name=\"pmid3493202\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Scott TG, Smyth CJ, Keane CT |title=In vitro adhesiveness and biotype of Gardnerella vaginalis strains in relation to the occurrence of clue cells in vaginal discharges |journal=Genitourinary medicine |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=47&ndash;53 |date=February 1987 |pmid=3493202 |pmc=1194007 |doi= 10.1136/sti.63.1.47|url=}}</ref> a group of Gram-variable bacteria. This bacterial infection is characterized by a foul, fishy smelling, thin gray [[vaginal discharge]], and an increase in vaginal [[pH]] from around 4.5 to over 5.5.\n<ref>https://www.prescriptiondoctor.com/bacterial-vaginosis</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.webmd.com/hw/health_guide_atoz/aa73146.asp Overview] at [[WebMD]]\n* [http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_od5PmBTqqUM/TShvTO5WoWI/AAAAAAAAGVw/XnyyVF7OgRQ/s1600/Clue%2BCell.jpg Clue cell in Gram stain ] at [http://thunderhouse4-yuri.blogspot.cz/2010/11/bacterial-vaginosis.html Fun With Microbiology]\n* [http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/akuserijaen/Images/29%20skyrelis%20pav.4.jpg Clue cell in Papanicolaou stain] at the [http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/akuserijaen/Laboratory%20medicine/29-Oncocytologic_investigation%20engl.html http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/]\n\n[[Category:Epithelial cells]]\n\n\n{{pathology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Clue cells - CDC PHIL 3720.jpg|thumb|right|Bacteria obscuring the borders of vaginal epithelial cells, giving them a stippled appearance]]\n[[File:Vaginal wet mount with a clue cell.jpg|thumb|right|[[Vaginal wet mount]] with [[sodium chloride|NaCl]] preparation, showing a clue cell at bottom left, and two normal epithelial cells.]]\n'''Clue cells''' are [[epithelial]] cells of the [[vagina]] that get their distinctive stippled appearance by being covered with [[bacteria]]. The etymology behind the term \"clue\" cell derives from the original research article from Gardner and Dukes describing the characteristic cells. The name was chosen for its brevity in describing the [[sine qua non]] of [[bacterial vaginosis]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gardner|first=Herman|author2=Dukes, Charles|title=Haemophilus vaginalis vaginitis: A newly defined specific infection previously classified \"nonspecific\" vaginitis|journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology|date=May 1955|pages=962\u2013976|pmid=14361525|volume=69|issue=5|doi=10.1016/0002-9378(55)90095-8}}<!--|accessdate=24 January 2013--></ref>\n\nThey are a [[medical sign]] of bacterial vaginosis, particularly that caused by ''[[Gardnerella vaginalis]]'',<ref name=\"pmid3493202\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Scott TG, Smyth CJ, Keane CT |title=In vitro adhesiveness and biotype of Gardnerella vaginalis strains in relation to the occurrence of clue cells in vaginal discharges |journal=Genitourinary medicine |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=47&ndash;53 |date=February 1987 |pmid=3493202 |pmc=1194007 |doi= 10.1136/sti.63.1.47|url=}}</ref> a group of Gram-variable bacteria. This bacterial infection is characterized by a foul, fishy smelling, thin gray [[vaginal discharge]], and an increase in vaginal [[pH]] from around 4.5 to over 5.5.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.webmd.com/hw/health_guide_atoz/aa73146.asp Overview] at [[WebMD]]\n* [http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_od5PmBTqqUM/TShvTO5WoWI/AAAAAAAAGVw/XnyyVF7OgRQ/s1600/Clue%2BCell.jpg Clue cell in Gram stain ] at [http://thunderhouse4-yuri.blogspot.cz/2010/11/bacterial-vaginosis.html Fun With Microbiology]\n* [http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/akuserijaen/Images/29%20skyrelis%20pav.4.jpg Clue cell in Papanicolaou stain] at the [http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/akuserijaen/Laboratory%20medicine/29-Oncocytologic_investigation%20engl.html http://eknygos.lsmuni.lt/]\n\n[[Category:Epithelial cells]]\n\n\n{{pathology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "42.98.90.31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clue_cell"}
{"title_page": "Alex Sharman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Alex Sharman\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Alex Sharman\n| nickname =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = [[Tasmania, Australia]]\n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_position = \n| ru_clubyears =\n| ru_proclubs = \n| ru_clubcaps =   \n| ru_clubpoints =\n| ru_clubupdate = \n| ru_nationalteam = {{nrut|Paraguay}}\n| ru_nationalyears = 2008\u20132010\n| ru_nationalcaps =\n| ru_nationalpoints = \n| ru_ntupdate=\n| rl_position = \n| rl_amateuryears =\n| rl_amateurclubs = \n}}\n\n'''Alex Sharman''' (born in [[Tasmania, Australia]]) is an [[Australian Paraguayan]] retired [[rugby union]] player who played for the University of Sydney (NSW, Australia), Falkirk (Scotland), Hinckley and Clifton Rugby Clubs (England), St. Louis Ramblers (USA),<ref>http://www.ramblers.org/rambler-awards/</ref> Rugby La Vila (Spain), San Jose Rugby Club and CURDA (Paraguay) and the [[Paraguay national rugby union team]].<ref>http://rugbyguarani.blogspot.com.au/2011/07/historia-del-rugby-en-paraguay.html</ref> Alex was the first Australian born player to represent Paraguay in rugby.\n\n==Early life==\nSharman was born in [[Hobart]], Tasmania, and started playing rugby at [[The Hutchins School]],<ref>http://www.hutchins.tas.edu.au/assets/HSOBA_Ivied_Tower_Newsletter_Nov_2013.pdf</ref> Captaining the School to a Premiership and also Captaining Tasmania at Underage level. Both of his brothers were also rugby players, who represented Tasmania and spent time playing in Europe.\n\n==Sydney==\nHe moved to Sydney at 17 to study and play a higher level of rugby, playing for [[Sydney Uni Football Club]] between 1995 and 2002 and winning a number of colts and lower grade Premierships. He made his first grade debut in the semi-finals of the Shute Shield in 2000.\n\n==Europe and American rugby==\nIn 2002 he left Australia to travel the world and play rugby. He played seasons for [[Falkirk RFC]] (Scotland) in 2002, followed by Hinckley [[Hinckley RFC]] (England) in 2002-3 and [[Clifton Rugby Football Club]](England) in 2003-4. In 2003, he was called up to play for an understrength Fijian side in a match against Bristol rugby.\n\nIn February 2004, Sharman moved to the U.S.A. where he played for the [[St. Louis Ramblers]] (Missouri) for 6 months.\n\nHe then moved to La Villajoyosa, Spain, where he spent 2 years playing for [[CR La Vila]]. He became player-coach of La Vila in December 2004, holding that position until December 2005 when he broke his ankle.\n\n==Paraguay==\nIn February 2006, unsure if he would be able to play rugby again due to his broken ankle, Sharman moved to Paraguay for personal reasons. Sharman resumed playing rugby later that year for the San Jose Rugby Club in Asuncion.\n\nAfter performing strongly for his club in the following years, in 2008 he was selected in the training squad for that years [[2008 South American Rugby Championship \"B\"]] and made his debut for the [[Paraguay national rugby union team]] in the Pre-Sudamericano tour of Rosario.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.com.py/deportes/poda-en-la-seleccion-1070520.html/ |title=Archivo no encontrado |publisher=Abc.com.py |date= |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\nDue to eligibility issues (he had not fulfilled the 36 months of residency required by the IRB) he had to leave the squad the week before the championship. At the end of that year Sharman was selected for Paraguay in the Cross-Border border tournament against Argentinian provinces.\n\nIn 2009, Sharman changed clubs to the CURDA club (Club Universitario de Rugby De Asuncion).<ref>http://rugby-international.blogspot.com.au/2010_05_01_archive.html</ref> After finally fulfilling IRB residency requirements in February 2009, Sharman made his test debut for Paraguay in May 2010, becoming the first Australian born player to represent Paraguay in the [[2009 South American Rugby Championship \"A\"]] in Montevideo, Uruguay. Later that year he won the Paraguayan League with his club and also played for Paraguay in the Cross Border Competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.com.py/edicion-impresa/deportes/curda-es-hexacampeon-del-oficial-de-primera-34727.html/ |title=Archivo no encontrado |publisher=Abc.com.py |date= |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Sharman was again starting prop for the Yacares (the nickname of the Paraguayan National Rugby team) in the [[2010 South American Rugby Championship \"A\"]]Sudamericano A in Chile, playing tests against Chile, Uruguay and Brasil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consur.org/index.php/torneos/mayor-a/item/101-brasil-23-paraguay-18 |title=Brasil 23 - Paraguay 18 |publisher=Consur.org |date=2015-01-27 |accessdate=2015-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223233608/http://www.consur.org/index.php/torneos/mayor-a/item/101-brasil-23-paraguay-18 |archivedate=23 February 2015 }}</ref><ref>http://www.feruchi.cl/index.php?id=12&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=516&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=7&cHash=5b527c2a4f</ref><ref>http://www.rugbynews.com.uy/brasil-gano-otra-vez/</ref>\n\nIn 2011, political problems within Paraguayan rugby meant that the strongest clubs, including CURDA, did not allow their players to be selected for the South American Championship.\n\nHe retired from rugby at the end of 2012, after winning a second Paraguayan Rugby Union title with CURDA.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.abc.com.py/edicion-impresa/sociales/final-de-rugby-del-torneo-clausura-2012-de-powerade-492262.html |title=Final de rugby del Torneo Clausura 2012 de Powerade - Edicion Impresa - ABC Color |publisher=Abc.com.py |date=2012-12-19 |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharman, Alex}}\n[[Category:Paraguayan people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Alex Sharman\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Alex Sharman\n| nickname =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = [[Tasmania, Australia]]\n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_position = \n| ru_clubyears =\n| ru_proclubs = \n| ru_clubcaps =   \n| ru_clubpoints = ( \n| ru_clubupdate = \n| ru_nationalteam = {{nrut|Paraguay}}\n| ru_nationalyears = 2008\u20132010\n| ru_nationalcaps =\n| ru_nationalpoints = \n| ru_ntupdate=\n| rl_position = \n| rl_amateuryears =\n| rl_amateurclubs = \n}}\n\n'''Alex Sharman''' (born in [[Tasmania, Australia]]) is an [[Australian Paraguayan]] retired [[rugby union]] player who played for the University of Sydney (NSW, Australia), Falkirk (Scotland), Hinckley and Clifton Rugby Clubs (England), St. Louis Ramblers (USA),<ref>http://www.ramblers.org/rambler-awards/</ref> Rugby La Vila (Spain), San Jose Rugby Club and CURDA (Paraguay) and the [[Paraguay national rugby union team]].<ref>http://rugbyguarani.blogspot.com.au/2011/07/historia-del-rugby-en-paraguay.html</ref> Alex was the first Australian born player to represent Paraguay in rugby.\n\n==Early life==\nSharman was born in [[Hobart]], Tasmania, and started playing rugby at [[The Hutchins School]],<ref>http://www.hutchins.tas.edu.au/assets/HSOBA_Ivied_Tower_Newsletter_Nov_2013.pdf</ref> Captaining the School to a Premiership and also Captaining Tasmania at Underage level. Both of his brothers were also rugby players, who represented Tasmania and spent time playing in Europe.\n\n==Sydney==\nHe moved to Sydney at 17 to study and play a higher level of rugby, playing for [[Sydney Uni Football Club]] between 1995 and 2002 and winning a number of colts and lower grade Premierships. He made his first grade debut in the semi-finals of the Shute Shield in 2000.\n\n==Europe and American rugby==\nIn 2002 he left Australia to travel the world and play rugby. He played seasons for [[Falkirk RFC]] (Scotland) in 2002, followed by Hinckley [[Hinckley RFC]] (England) in 2002-3 and [[Clifton Rugby Football Club]](England) in 2003-4. In 2003, he was called up to play for an understength Fijian side in a match against Bristol rugby.\n\nIn February 2004, Sharman moved to the U.S.A. where he played for the [[St. Louis Ramblers]] (Missouri) for 6 months.\n\nHe then moved to La Villajoyosa, Spain, where he spent 2 years playing for [[CR La Vila]]. He became player-coach of La Vila in December 2004, holding that position until December 2005 when he broke his ankle.\n\n==Paraguay==\nIn February 2006, unsure if he would be able to play rugby again due to his broken ankle, Sharman moved to Paraguay for personal reasons. Sharman resumed playing rugby later that year for the San Jose Rugby Club in Asuncion.\n\nAfter performing strongly for his club in the following years, in 2008 he was selected in the training squad for that years [[2008 South American Rugby Championship \"B\"]] and made his debut for the [[Paraguay national rugby union team]] in the Pre-Sudamericano tour of Rosario.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.com.py/deportes/poda-en-la-seleccion-1070520.html/ |title=Archivo no encontrado |publisher=Abc.com.py |date= |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\nDue to eligibility issues (he had not fulfilled the 36 months of residency required by the IRB) he had to leave the squad the week before the championship. At the end of that year Sharman was selected for Paraguay in the Cross-Border border tournament against Argentinian provinces.\n\nIn 2009, Sharman changed clubs to the CURDA club (Club Universitario de Rugby De Asuncion).<ref>http://rugby-international.blogspot.com.au/2010_05_01_archive.html</ref> After finally fulfilling IRB residency requirements in February 2009, Sharman made his test debut for Paraguay in May 2010, becoming the first Australian born player to represent Paraguay in the [[2009 South American Rugby Championship \"A\"]] in Montevideo, Uruguay. Later that year he won the Paraguayan League with his club and also played for Paraguay in the Cross Border Competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.com.py/edicion-impresa/deportes/curda-es-hexacampeon-del-oficial-de-primera-34727.html/ |title=Archivo no encontrado |publisher=Abc.com.py |date= |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Sharman was again starting prop for the Yacares (the nickname of the Paraguayan National Rugby team) in the [[2010 South American Rugby Championship \"A\"]]Sudamericano A in Chile, playing tests against Chile, Uruguay and Brasil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consur.org/index.php/torneos/mayor-a/item/101-brasil-23-paraguay-18 |title=Brasil 23 - Paraguay 18 |publisher=Consur.org |date=2015-01-27 |accessdate=2015-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223233608/http://www.consur.org/index.php/torneos/mayor-a/item/101-brasil-23-paraguay-18 |archivedate=23 February 2015 }}</ref><ref>http://www.feruchi.cl/index.php?id=12&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=516&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=7&cHash=5b527c2a4f</ref><ref>http://www.rugbynews.com.uy/brasil-gano-otra-vez/</ref>\n\nIn 2011, political problems within Paraguayan rugby meant that the strongest clubs, including CURDA, did not allow their players to be selected for the South American Championship.\n\nHe retired from rugby at the end of 2012, after winning a second Paraguayan Rugby Union title with CURDA.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.abc.com.py/edicion-impresa/sociales/final-de-rugby-del-torneo-clausura-2012-de-powerade-492262.html |title=Final de rugby del Torneo Clausura 2012 de Powerade - Edicion Impresa - ABC Color |publisher=Abc.com.py |date=2012-12-19 |accessdate=2015-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharman, Alex}}\n[[Category:Paraguayan people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: understength \u2192 understrength", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Sharman"}
{"title_page": "A Death in the Desert", "text_new": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = A Death in the Desert\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Willa Cather]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = \n| published_in  = [[Scribner's Magazine]]\n| publication_type = [[Magazine]]\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = \n| pub_date      = 1903\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''\"A Death in the Desert\"''' is a short story by [[Willa Cather]]. It was first published in ''[[Scribner's Magazine|The Scribner's]]'' in January 1903.<ref>Willa Cather's Collected Short Fiction, University of Nebraska Press; Rev Ed edition, 1 Nov 1970, page 217</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nEverett is on a train from [[Holdrege, Nebraska]] to [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]]. He is a man that looks like his older prodigy brother Adriance\u2014this similarity haunts him throughout the entire novel and robs him of his own personality. He will always be Adriance's brother.\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Everett Hilgarde'''\n*'''Charley Gaylord'''\n*'''Two girls on the train'''.\n*'''Adriance Hilgarde'''\n*'''Katharine Gaylord'''\n*'''Maggie Gaylord'''\n*'''The Parson'''\n*'''Diana''', a chaste actress in New York City.\n\n==Allusions to other works==\n*Katharine Gaylord mentions [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Das Rheingold]]'', [[Edward Gibbon]]'s ''[[The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire]]'', and [[Heinrich Heine]]'s ''Florentine Nights''.\n\nMoreover, [[Gussie Davis]]' song \"In the Baggage Coach Ahead\" is mentioned - albeit 'in' is elided.<ref>Stouck, David, 'Review of ''The Troll Garden'', by Willa Cather', Great Plains Quarterly, 4:278</ref>\n\n==Literary significance and criticism==\nIt has been argued that the title of the story was influenced by Willa Cather's reading of [[Robert Browning]].<ref>Bernice Slote, 'Willa Cather and Her First Book', Willa Cather, ''April Twilights'', University of Nebraska Press, 1968, page xi</ref>\n\nAllusions to [[Alexandre Dumas, fils]]' ''[[The Lady of the Camellias|La dame aux camelias]]'' and [[Lucretius]]'s ''[[De rerum natura]]'' have also been found.<ref>Woodress, James, ''The Troll Garden'' by Willa Cather, Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1983b, p. 126</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://cather.unl.edu/ss012.html ''Full Text''] at the [http://cather.unl.edu ''Willa Cather Archive'']\n\n{{Cather}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death In The Desert, A}}\n[[Category:1903 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Willa Cather]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Scribner's Magazine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = A Death in the Desert\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Willa Cather]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = \n| published_in  = [[Scribner's Magazine]]\n| publication_type = [[Magazine]]\n| publisher     = \n| media_type    = \n| pub_date      = 1903\n| english_pub_date = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''\"A Death in the Desert\"''' is a short story by [[Willa Cather]]. It was first published in ''[[Scribner's Magazine|The Scribner's]]'' in January 1903.<ref>Willa Cather's Collected Short Fiction, University of Nebraska Press; Rev Ed edition, 1 Nov 1970, page 217</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nEverett is on a train from [[Holdrege, Nebraska]] to [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]]. He is a man that looks like his older prodigy brother Adriance\u2014this similarity haunts him throughout the entire novel and robs him of his own personality. He will always be Adriance's brother.\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Everett Hilgarde'''\n*'''Charley Gaylord'''\n*'''Two girls on the train'''.\n*'''Adriance Hilgarde'''\n*'''Katharine Gaylord'''\n*'''Maggie Gaylord'''\n*'''The Parson'''\n*'''Diana''', a chaste actress in New York City.\n\n==Allusions to other works==\n*Katharine Gaylord mentions [[Richard Wagner]]'s ''[[Das Rheingold]]'', [[Edward Gibbon]]'s ''[[The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire]]'', and [[Heinrich Heine]]'s ''Florentine Nights''.\n\nMoreover, [[Gussie Davis]]'s song ''In The Baggage Coach Ahead'' is mentioned - albeit 'in' is elided.<ref>Stouck, David, 'Review of ''The Troll Garden'', by Willa Cather', Great Plains Quarterly, 4:278</ref>\n\n==Literary significance and criticism==\nIt has been argued that the title of the story was influenced by Willa Cather's reading of [[Robert Browning]].<ref>Bernice Slote, 'Willa Cather and Her First Book', Willa Cather, ''April Twilights'', University of Nebraska Press, 1968, page xi</ref>\n\nAllusions to [[Alexandre Dumas, fils]]' ''[[The Lady of the Camellias|La dame aux camelias]]'' and [[Lucretius]]'s ''[[De rerum natura]]'' have also been found.<ref>Woodress, James, ''The Troll Garden'' by Willa Cather, Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1983b, p. 126</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://cather.unl.edu/ss012.html ''Full Text''] at the [http://cather.unl.edu ''Willa Cather Archive'']\n\n{{Cather}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Death In The Desert, A}}\n[[Category:1903 short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Willa Cather]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in Scribner's Magazine]]\n", "name_user": "JohnRogers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAllusions to other works:Wikify song title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Death_in_the_Desert"}
{"title_page": "Abroad in Japan", "text_new": "{{short description|A Japan-focused YouTube channel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name            = Abroad in Japan\n| logo            = File:Abroad In Japan logo.png\n| logo caption    =\n| image           =\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Christopher Broad\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1990|04|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place     = \n| nationality     = British\n|residence      = [[Sendai]], [[Miyagi Prefecture]], Japan\n| alma_mater      = \n| occupation      = YouTube influencer, filmmaker\n| website         = {{URL|abroadinjapan.com}}\n| pseudonym       = <!-- use for individuals only -->\n| channel_name    = cmbroad44\n| years_active    = 2012 \u2013 present\n| genre           = vlog, podcast, documentary\n| subscribers     = 1,470,000+\n| subscriber_date = February 2020\n| views           = 173,000,000+\n| view_date       = February 2020\n| network         = <!-- multi-channel network (MCN) to which the channel has signed (past and/or present), if any -->\n| associated_acts = Radio Stakhanov, Tokyo Creative\n| silver_button   = yes\n| silver_year     = 2014\n| gold_button     = yes\n| gold_year       = 2018\n| diamond_button     = <!-- yes/no; only use if the individual/channel has been awarded with a gold play button by YouTube -->\n| diamond_year       = <!-- year in which the channel reached 1,000,000 subscribers -->\n| stats_update    =\n}}\n'''Chris Broad''' (born 21 April 1990), known online as '''Abroad in Japan,''' is a British [[YouTuber]], filmmaker, inventor of the green tea sake and podcast host. He focuses on videos about Japanese culture, Japanese food and travel in [[Japan]], primarily in the [[T\u014dhoku region]].<ref name=\"Like a party\">{{cite web|author=Atsuko Matsumoto|title=Videos \u2018like a party\u2019 look for the real Japan|url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0005857938|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun|The Japan News]]|date=13 July 2019|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBroad briefly appeared on the TV series [[Robot Wars (TV series)|''Robot Wars'']] in the UK, where his father and team were regular contestants, with their robot Killertron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acast.com/abroadinjapan/abroadinjapan-mythsaboutjapan-|title=Abroad in Japan: Myths about Japan! {{!}} Abroad in Japan on acast|last=acast|date=4 April 2018|website=acast|language=en|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBroad studied English Language and Business at the [[University of Kent]] from 2009 to 2012 before moving to [[Sakata, Yamagata]] to teach English as a part of the [[JET Programme]]. He has since left the programme and moved to [[Sendai]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A foreigner living in Japan. A charm of Miyagi from a YouTuber. Interview / Mr. Chris Broad|url=https://www.soumu.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/17hisaichi/hp/douga/miyagi12.html|work=Stories of Miyagi|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==YouTube channel==\nUpon moving to Sakata, Yamagata to teach as a part of the JET Programme in 2012, Broad decided to vlog about some of his experiences as a foreigner living in the rural T\u014dhoku region. The subjects of videos included topics like what it's like to drive in Japan, [[KFC]] as a mainstay of every Japanese Christmas, and [[love hotel]]s. He later moved to [[Sendai]] to remain in the region, but to be somewhere better connected to the rest of the country to expand his business opportunities as an influencer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Shizuka|title=Get To Know Chris Broad from Abroad in Japan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YG9zICtFZVw|date=30 March 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> As the channel grew in notability, Broad began to make more travel-themed videos, such as a video describing a trip to [[Aomori (city)|Aomori]] where he visited the city's [[Aomori Nebuta Matsuri|Nebuta]] museum and another where he visited [[Hokkaido]] with his close friend Natsuki Aso, who often appears in Chris' videos.\n\nOn 29 August 2017, Broad was visiting a town in [[Aomori Prefecture]] near [[Shirakami-Sanchi]] [[wilderness area]] when he was woken up by the [[J-Alert]] being triggered by the [[North Korean August 2017 missile launch over Japan]]. He posted a video about how rude it was that they would carry out their test so early in the morning and proceeded to criticize the regime of [[Kim Jong-un]]. The video was featured as \"Trending\" the day it was posted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saunokonoko|first=Mark|title=Japan wakes up to TVs being taken over as North Korean missile whizzed overhead|url=https://www.9news.com.au/world/2017/08/30/12/16/japan-woke-up-to-sirens-and-tvs-being-taken-over-as-north-korean-missile-whizzed-overhead|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> It then went on to attract national attention in Japan, with Broad being selected to represent the word \"J-Alert\" in Japan's annual Words of the Year event.\n\nOn 31 May 2018, Broad released the documentary film ''Natsuki: The Movie'' telling the story of Broad and his friend Natsuki's journey to Europe.<ref>{{Cite web||last=Abroad in Japan|title=Natsuki: The Movie (Life in Japan Documentary)|date=31 May 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WLWZBeX-isM|access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tessa Randello|title=Japan's YouTubers go long with crowdfunded content|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/09/national/media-national/japans-youtubers-go-long-crowdfunded-content/#.XaLF9FX7TIUI|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=9 June 2018|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 2018, Broad started his \"Journey Across Japan\" series featuring various YouTubers, such as [[The Anime Man]], and his friends as he travels across Japan by bike, documenting local customs and daily life along the way.\n\n=== Documentary work ===\nThe channel also has featured some documentary-style videos. In addition to the Natsuki movie mentioned above, one focused on the effects of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] on the citizens of [[Kesennuma]] and how they and external powers are working to rebuild their city's image and livelihood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ObSo4VxCFzs|title=What Happened In Japan After The Tsunami?|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> Broad noted that the aversion to the area because of the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] bothered him and that caused him to work on documentaries about the area, including one that is in development that will focus on the positive aspects of life in [[Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima]].<ref name=\"Like a party2\">{{cite web|url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0005857938|title=Videos \u2018like a party\u2019 look for the real Japan|author=Atsuko Matsumoto|date=13 July 2019|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun|The Japan News]]|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, he released a documentary interview of the [[Rock music|rock]] artist, [[Hyde (musician)|Hyde]] during the artist's performances at [[Zepp]] Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jrocknews.com/2019/12/youtuber-spends-week-with-hyde.html|title=British youtuber spends a week with HYDE|work=J Rock News|date=22 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Podcast==\nTogether with [[Pete Donaldson]], Broad presents a weekly Abroad in Japan series of podcasts on Radio Stakhanov about Japanese culture, current events, and cuisine. Some recurring topics of the series are the [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte]] [[soft serve]], Coolish and a pizza vending machine that was once functioning in [[Hiroshima]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza vending machine attracts crowds in Hiroshima|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/09/06/business/pizza-vending-machine-attracts-crowds-hiroshima/#.XXrk_GaRW00|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> The pair also talk about Japan-related stories and questions submitted by their audience by email in a segment they call the \"Fax Machine\" as a jest towards the obsolete method of communication that is still commonly used in many Japanese workplaces.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin Fackler|title=In High-Tech Japan, the Fax Machines Roll On|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/world/asia/in-japan-the-fax-machine-is-anything-but-a-relic.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=13 February 2013|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Abroad in Japan- A Japanese culture broadcast|url=https://radiostakhanov.com/abroadinjapan/|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nBroad spoke at a [[List of TEDx conferences|TEDx conference]] at [[Tohoku University]] where he spoke about the power of YouTube and encouraged the audience to share their experiences with the world through the platform.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your audience is waiting|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zX_rqdSohyA|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2017, Broad was the host of a documentary about cats in Japanese culture called ''Cat Nation'' (despite being allergic to cats) where he travelled throughout Japan to document the cat-centered activities or places, such as visiting the [[Wakayama Electric Railway]] where a cat named [[Tama (cat)|Tama]] became a tourist attraction after it became the [[station master]] of [[Kishi Station (Wakayama)|Kishi Station]].<ref>{{cite web|title=''Cat Nation: A Film About Japan's Crazy Cat Culture.''|url=https://www.catnation.tv/|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Collaborators==\n* {{nihongo|Natsuki Aso|\u963f\u8613 \u590f\u6a39|Aso Natsuki}} \u2013 presenter, amateur musician and owner of a beauty salon in Yamagata, Japan\n* {{nihongo|Ryotaro Sakurai|\u6afb\u4e95 \u4eae\u592a\u90ce|Sakurai Ry\u014dtar\u014d}} \u2013 Co-presenter and Director of LifeBridge Inc<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jp.linkedin.com/in/ryotaro-sakurai-619431b|title=Ryotaro Sakurai's LinkedIn|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TEDx Talks|title=Learning outside Japan, telling Tohoku to the world {{!}} Ryotaro Sakurai {{!}} TEDxTohokuUniversity|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XL0SS8CChOQ|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Sharmander|Sharla]] (formerly Sharla in Japan and now known as Sharmander) \u2013 Guest (various appearances)\n* [[Pete Donaldson]] \u2013 Podcast co-host, former London radio [[DJ]] and [[Japanophile]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5957128/ Abroad in Japan on IMDb]\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:British video bloggers]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A Japan-focused YouTube channel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name            = Abroad in Japan\n| logo            = File:Abroad In Japan logo.png\n| logo caption    =\n| image           =\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Christopher Broad\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1990|04|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place     = \n| nationality     = British\n|residence      = [[Sendai]], [[Miyagi Prefecture]], Japan\n| alma_mater      = \n| occupation      = YouTube influencer, filmmaker\n| website         = {{URL|abroadinjapan.com}}\n| pseudonym       = <!-- use for individuals only -->\n| channel_name    = cmbroad44\n| years_active    = 2012 \u2013 present\n| genre           = vlog, podcast, documentary\n| subscribers     = 1,470,000+\n| subscriber_date = February 2020\n| views           = 173,000,000+\n| view_date       = February 2020\n| network         = <!-- multi-channel network (MCN) to which the channel has signed (past and/or present), if any -->\n| associated_acts = Radio Stakhanov, Tokyo Creative\n| silver_button   = yes\n| silver_year     = 2014\n| gold_button     = yes\n| gold_year       = 2018\n| diamond_button     = <!-- yes/no; only use if the individual/channel has been awarded with a gold play button by YouTube -->\n| diamond_year       = <!-- year in which the channel reached 1,000,000 subscribers -->\n| stats_update    =\n}}\n'''Chris Broad''' (born 21 April 1990), known online as '''Abroad in Japan,''' is a British [[YouTuber]], filmmaker, and podcast host. He focuses on videos about Japanese culture, Japanese food and travel in [[Japan]], primarily in the [[T\u014dhoku region]].<ref name=\"Like a party\">{{cite web|author=Atsuko Matsumoto|title=Videos \u2018like a party\u2019 look for the real Japan|url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0005857938|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun|The Japan News]]|date=13 July 2019|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBroad briefly appeared on the TV series [[Robot Wars (TV series)|''Robot Wars'']] in the UK, where his father and team were regular contestants, with their robot Killertron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acast.com/abroadinjapan/abroadinjapan-mythsaboutjapan-|title=Abroad in Japan: Myths about Japan! {{!}} Abroad in Japan on acast|last=acast|date=4 April 2018|website=acast|language=en|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nBroad studied English Language and Business at the [[University of Kent]] from 2009 to 2012 before moving to [[Sakata, Yamagata]] to teach English as a part of the [[JET Programme]]. He has since left the programme and moved to [[Sendai]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A foreigner living in Japan. A charm of Miyagi from a YouTuber. Interview / Mr. Chris Broad|url=https://www.soumu.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/17hisaichi/hp/douga/miyagi12.html|work=Stories of Miyagi|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==YouTube channel==\nUpon moving to Sakata, Yamagata to teach as a part of the JET Programme in 2012, Broad decided to vlog about some of his experiences as a foreigner living in the rural T\u014dhoku region. The subjects of videos included topics like what it's like to drive in Japan, [[KFC]] as a mainstay of every Japanese Christmas, and [[love hotel]]s. He later moved to [[Sendai]] to remain in the region, but to be somewhere better connected to the rest of the country to expand his business opportunities as an influencer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Shizuka|title=Get To Know Chris Broad from Abroad in Japan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YG9zICtFZVw|date=30 March 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> As the channel grew in notability, Broad began to make more travel-themed videos, such as a video describing a trip to [[Aomori (city)|Aomori]] where he visited the city's [[Aomori Nebuta Matsuri|Nebuta]] museum and another where he visited [[Hokkaido]] with his close friend Natsuki Aso, who often appears in Chris' videos.\n\nOn 29 August 2017, Broad was visiting a town in [[Aomori Prefecture]] near [[Shirakami-Sanchi]] [[wilderness area]] when he was woken up by the [[J-Alert]] being triggered by the [[North Korean August 2017 missile launch over Japan]]. He posted a video about how rude it was that they would carry out their test so early in the morning and proceeded to criticize the regime of [[Kim Jong-un]]. The video was featured as \"Trending\" the day it was posted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saunokonoko|first=Mark|title=Japan wakes up to TVs being taken over as North Korean missile whizzed overhead|url=https://www.9news.com.au/world/2017/08/30/12/16/japan-woke-up-to-sirens-and-tvs-being-taken-over-as-north-korean-missile-whizzed-overhead|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> It then went on to attract national attention in Japan, with Broad being selected to represent the word \"J-Alert\" in Japan's annual Words of the Year event.\n\nOn 31 May 2018, Broad released the documentary film ''Natsuki: The Movie'' telling the story of Broad and his friend Natsuki's journey to Europe.<ref>{{Cite web||last=Abroad in Japan|title=Natsuki: The Movie (Life in Japan Documentary)|date=31 May 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WLWZBeX-isM|access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tessa Randello|title=Japan's YouTubers go long with crowdfunded content|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/09/national/media-national/japans-youtubers-go-long-crowdfunded-content/#.XaLF9FX7TIUI|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=9 June 2018|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 2018, Broad started his \"Journey Across Japan\" series featuring various YouTubers, such as [[The Anime Man]], and his friends as he travels across Japan by bike, documenting local customs and daily life along the way.\n\n=== Documentary work ===\nThe channel also has featured some documentary-style videos. In addition to the Natsuki movie mentioned above, one focused on the effects of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] on the citizens of [[Kesennuma]] and how they and external powers are working to rebuild their city's image and livelihood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ObSo4VxCFzs|title=What Happened In Japan After The Tsunami?|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> Broad noted that the aversion to the area because of the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] bothered him and that caused him to work on documentaries about the area, including one that is in development that will focus on the positive aspects of life in [[Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima]].<ref name=\"Like a party2\">{{cite web|url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0005857938|title=Videos \u2018like a party\u2019 look for the real Japan|author=Atsuko Matsumoto|date=13 July 2019|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun|The Japan News]]|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, he released a documentary interview of the [[Rock music|rock]] artist, [[Hyde (musician)|Hyde]] during the artist's performances at [[Zepp]] Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jrocknews.com/2019/12/youtuber-spends-week-with-hyde.html|title=British youtuber spends a week with HYDE|work=J Rock News|date=22 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Podcast==\nTogether with [[Pete Donaldson]], Broad presents a weekly Abroad in Japan series of podcasts on Radio Stakhanov about Japanese culture, current events, and cuisine. Some recurring topics of the series are the [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte]] [[soft serve]], Coolish and a pizza vending machine that was once functioning in [[Hiroshima]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza vending machine attracts crowds in Hiroshima|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/09/06/business/pizza-vending-machine-attracts-crowds-hiroshima/#.XXrk_GaRW00|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> The pair also talk about Japan-related stories and questions submitted by their audience by email in a segment they call the \"Fax Machine\" as a jest towards the obsolete method of communication that is still commonly used in many Japanese workplaces.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin Fackler|title=In High-Tech Japan, the Fax Machines Roll On|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/world/asia/in-japan-the-fax-machine-is-anything-but-a-relic.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=13 February 2013|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Abroad in Japan- A Japanese culture broadcast|url=https://radiostakhanov.com/abroadinjapan/|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nBroad spoke at a [[List of TEDx conferences|TEDx conference]] at [[Tohoku University]] where he spoke about the power of YouTube and encouraged the audience to share their experiences with the world through the platform.<ref>{{cite web|title=Your audience is waiting|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zX_rqdSohyA|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2017, Broad was the host of a documentary about cats in Japanese culture called ''Cat Nation'' (despite being allergic to cats) where he travelled throughout Japan to document the cat-centered activities or places, such as visiting the [[Wakayama Electric Railway]] where a cat named [[Tama (cat)|Tama]] became a tourist attraction after it became the [[station master]] of [[Kishi Station (Wakayama)|Kishi Station]].<ref>{{cite web|title=''Cat Nation: A Film About Japan's Crazy Cat Culture.''|url=https://www.catnation.tv/|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Collaborators==\n* {{nihongo|Natsuki Aso|\u963f\u8613 \u590f\u6a39|Aso Natsuki}} \u2013 presenter, amateur musician and owner of a beauty salon in Yamagata, Japan\n* {{nihongo|Ryotaro Sakurai|\u6afb\u4e95 \u4eae\u592a\u90ce|Sakurai Ry\u014dtar\u014d}} \u2013 Co-presenter and Director of LifeBridge Inc<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jp.linkedin.com/in/ryotaro-sakurai-619431b|title=Ryotaro Sakurai's LinkedIn|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=TEDx Talks|title=Learning outside Japan, telling Tohoku to the world {{!}} Ryotaro Sakurai {{!}} TEDxTohokuUniversity|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XL0SS8CChOQ|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Sharmander|Sharla]] (formerly Sharla in Japan and now known as Sharmander) \u2013 Guest (various appearances)\n* [[Pete Donaldson]] \u2013 Podcast co-host, former London radio [[DJ]] and [[Japanophile]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5957128/ Abroad in Japan on IMDb]\n\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:British video bloggers]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n", "name_user": "118.210.201.133", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abroad_in_Japan"}
